# Inner Join:
An inner Join returns only the rows where there is a match in both tables based on the specified columns.

When to use: Use an inner Join when you want to retireve only the records that have corresponding entries in both tables.

# Left Outer join:
A left outer join returns all the rows from the left table and the matched rows from the right table.
If there is not match, the result is NULL on the right side.

# Right outer join:
A right outer returns all the rows from the right table and matching rows froms from the left table.
If there is no match, the result is NULL on the left side.

# Left Anti Join: A left anit join returnss only the rows from the left table that do not have a matching rows in the right table.

When to use: Use a left Anti join when we need to identify records in the primary table that lack correcponding entries in thee secondary table.


# Right Anti Join: A right anti join returns only the rows from the right table that do not have a matching rows in the left table.

When to Use: Use a Right Anti Join when you need to identify records in the secondary table that lack corresponding entries in the primary table.

# Full Outter Join: A full outer join returns all rows when there is a match in either left or right table.
This means it includes all records from both tables, with NULL values where there is no match.
